## 5. Market Analysis

- **Industry size and trends:** US aircraft parts distribution (NAICS 423860 sub-segment / IBISWorld "Aircraft Parts Distributors") is a multi-billion-dollar, fragmented market. Aerospace aftermarket demand has been strong post-pandemic on high commercial fleet utilization, constrained new-aircraft delivery rates keeping older airframes flying, and sustained military sustainment spending. Aerospace valuation multiples have risen steadily since 2024.
- **Growth drivers and barriers:** Drivers — aging global fleets, MRO backlogs, ITAR/export-licensed niches with high barriers to entry, military sustainment budgets. Barriers — inventory working-capital intensity, OEM channel control, parts traceability/airworthiness documentation requirements, cyclicality tied to airline capex and defense appropriations.
- **Competitive landscape (peer benchmarks):**
  - **AAR Corp** — large public aerospace distributor/MRO; acquired ADI (Aerospace) in Sept 2025 for $146M on ~$149M revenue / $15.2M EBITDA — an implied ~9.6x EBITDA multiple at scale.
  - **VSE Corp (VSE Aviation)** — public aviation distribution/repair consolidator; acquired Kellstrom Aerospace and Turbine Weld; ~$1.1B 2025 revenue. Demonstrates an active roll-up market for parts distributors.
  - **Small private aircraft-parts distributors** — niche shops typically transact at low single-digit SDE multiples (~2–3x SDE for sub-$1M-earnings businesses), well below the 8–10x commanded by scaled platforms. This target sits firmly in the small-private tier.

